This is the story of how I almost got kidnapped and ended up in the trunk of a red Mazda.
One day after I had completed my design studies, I held a backyard sale.
A guy in the red Mazda stopped and looked at my things.
He bought one of my artworks.
He was alone in the city and was currently on a road trip through the entire country. After that, he would join the Peace Corps.
I invited him for a beer. He enthusiastically told me how he wanted to change the world.
It got late. I became tired.
While we were paying the bill, I made the mistake of asking him: "Where are you staying tonight?"
He made the whole thing even worse: "I don't know yet."
And I thought, "Oh, man!
What do I do now?
Who doesn't know the situation?
Do I have to offer a place to sleep now?
But I just met him! He says he's going to the Peace Corps, but I don't know if he really plans to do that. I don't want to end up kidnapped in the trunk of a Mazda!
That's a small trunk!
Then I heard myself say, "I have an air mattress. You can sleep in my living room."
A voice in my head said, "Uh, excuse me?"
At night, I lay in bed, staring at the ceiling and thinking, "Oh man! What have I gotten myself into?
A total stranger is sleeping in my living room.
What if he's crazy?
I got so scared that I got out of bed, tiptoed to the door, and locked my bedroom door.
But he wasn't crazy.
We are still in touch.
The artwork he bought from me is now hanging in his classroom. He is now a teacher.
That was my first experience as a host. It completely changed my perspective.
Maybe the people who were sold to me as strangers in childhood were actually friends just waiting to be discovered?
Hosting people on my air mattress became normal for me. When I moved to San Francisco, I took the air mattress with me.
Let's make a time jump, two years later...
I am unemployed, almost broke, my roommate is moving out, and the rent is being increased.
I learned that there was a design conference in the city at that time. All hotels were fully booked.
I believe creativity can turn fear into fun.
I wrote to my best friend and new roommate Brian Chesky: "Brian, I've been thinking about how we could make some extra money. Our apartment will become a designer bed and breakfast. Young designers can stay with us, with Wi-Fi and a desk included, plus a mattress and breakfast every morning.
Ha!"
We created a website and thus founded "Luftmatratze und Frühstück" [AIRBed aNd Breakfast = Airbnb].
Three happy guests were allowed to sleep on the air mattress on the wooden floor for 20 dollars at our place.
They thought it was great, and so did we.
I'm sure our cheese and ham omelets tasted completely different because we made them for our guests.
We toured the city with them. When we said goodbye to our last guest and the door closed behind them, Brian and I stared at each other.
Had we just discovered that we could simultaneously make new friends and pay our rent?
Things started rolling.
My former roommate, Nate Blecharczyk, joined us as a developer.
We wanted to find out if we could turn it into a business concept.
So we presented ourselves to the investors: "We want to create a website where people can publicly post pictures of their private spaces, their bedrooms, their bathrooms -- the kind of rooms you close the doors to when guests come over.
Through the internet, they can then invite complete strangers to stay with them.
That will be the next big thing!
