In the beginning, we made some mistakes.
It was difficult for people to leave negative reviews.
Ultimately, we decided to wait until both the host and the guest had submitted their reviews before posting them online.
Last week we discovered something new.
We conducted a study with Stanford. We examined how likely it is that people trust each other, depending on how similar they are in terms of age and place of residence.
Unsurprisingly, we trust the people most who are most similar to us.
The more differences we find, the less we trust.
This is a natural social bias.
It gets exciting when you add a person's reputation - in our case through reviews.
If you have less than three reviews, nothing changes.
But if you have more than ten, everything changes.
A good reputation stands out from commonalities.
So the right design can help us overcome some of our deeply rooted preferences.
Furthermore, we learned that trust depends on how much one reveals about themselves.
